main event: On 6 February 1952, two unidentified round, silver-colored objects were reported flying at a high rate of speed at approximately 20,000 feet over El Paso, Texas. However, the Control Tower at El Paso International Airport did not observe any unidentified objects at that time. As a result, no further investigation was conducted by the office.
interesting points: The objects were first observed at 1630 hours and remained in sight for approximately 5 minutes.
The information received described the objects as round in shape, silver in color, and traveling at a high rate of speed at around 20,000 feet in altitude.
No other reports regarding visual sightings of unidentified aerial objects in the area had been received by the office.
Photographs of the unidentified objects were found to be caused by small flaws in the emulsion of the negatives, and the investigation was requested by the Directorate of Intelligence of the USAF.
The objects appeared indistinct and slightly elongated in the developed film, and the source used for photography was a 35mm cannon camera with a motor telemoto lens.
witnesses: Captain John D. Ruick, USAF, 1st Strategic Support Squadron
photographs: Yes, photographs of the unidentified objects were found to be caused by small flaws in the emulsion of the negatives.
